%N A395928 Irregular triangle read by rows in which the row n lists the partition of n into the minimum number of prime parts, chosen greedily in decreasing order.
%C A395928 The representation of the partitions (for fixed n) is as (weakly) decreasing list of the parts.
%e A395928 The irregular triangle begins as:
%e A395928    2;
%e A395928    3;
%e A395928    2, 2;
%e A395928    5;
%e A395928    3, 3;
%e A395928    7;
%e A395928    5, 3;
%e A395928    7, 2;
%e A395928    7, 3;
%e A395928   11;
%e A395928    7, 5;
%e A395928   13;
%e A395928   11, 3;
%e A395928   13, 2;
%e A395928   13, 3;
%e A395928   17;
%e A395928   13, 5;
%e A395928   19;
%e A395928   17, 3;
%e A395928   19, 2;
%e A395928   19, 3;
%e A395928   23;
%e A395928   19, 5;
%e A395928   23, 2;
%e A395928   23, 3;
%e A395928   23, 2, 2;
%e A395928   ...
%t A395928 nmax=50; With[{primes = Prime[Range[PrimePi[nmax]]]}, Flatten[Table[First[IntegerPartitions[n, All, primes, 1]], {n, 2, nmax}]]]
%Y A395928 First column gives A335285.
%Y A395928 Row lengths give A051034.
%Y A395928 Cf. A000040, A000041, A354762.
